---
import CodeBlock from "../components/CodeBlock.astro";
import Callout from "../components/Callout.astro";
---

<div class="space-y-8">
  <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-zinc-300">
    Before modern tooling existed, building a website meant creating raw files
    by hand and opening them directly in a browser. No build step, no dev
    server, no package manager. Just you, a text editor, and a folder of files.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock title="index.html — the entire app in one file" accent="amber">
    <span
      class="text-zinc-300"
      set:html={`<span class="text-zinc-400">&lt;!-- Every library loaded via a &lt;script&gt; tag --&gt;\n&lt;!-- ORDER MATTERS — load jQuery before your code! --&gt;\n</span><span class="text-red-400">&lt;script</span><span class="text-amber-300"> src</span><span class="text-zinc-400">=</span><span class="text-emerald-400">"libs/jquery-3.2.1.min.js"</span><span class="text-red-400">&gt;</span><span class="text-red-400">&lt;/script&gt;\n</span><span class="text-red-400">&lt;script</span><span class="text-amber-300"> src</span><span class="text-zinc-400">=</span><span class="text-emerald-400">"libs/bootstrap.min.js"</span><span class="text-red-400">&gt;</span><span class="text-red-400">&lt;/script&gt;\n</span><span class="text-red-400">&lt;script</span><span class="text-amber-300"> src</span><span class="text-zinc-400">=</span><span class="text-emerald-400">"libs/lodash.min.js"</span><span class="text-red-400">&gt;</span><span class="text-red-400">&lt;/script&gt;\n</span><span class="text-red-400">&lt;script</span><span class="text-amber-300"> src</span><span class="text-zinc-400">=</span><span class="text-emerald-400">"js/utils.js"</span><span class="text-red-400">&gt;</span><span class="text-red-400">&lt;/script&gt;\n</span><span class="text-red-400">&lt;script</span><span class="text-amber-300"> src</span><span class="text-zinc-400">=</span><span class="text-emerald-400">"js/app.js"</span><span class="text-red-400">&gt;</span><span class="text-red-400">&lt;/script&gt;\n</span><span class="text-zinc-400">\n&lt;!-- Move one script above another? Everything breaks. --&gt;</span>`}
    />
  </CodeBlock>

  <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
    {
      [
        {
          title: "No Modules",
          desc: "Every .js file shared the same global scope. Your variable names could collide with a library's. Naming things was a minefield.",
          icon: "🌍",
        },
        {
          title: "Manual Dependencies",
          desc: "Want to use a library? Download the .js file, drop it in a folder, add a \u003Cscript\u003E tag. Want to update it? Do it all again.",
          icon: "📦",
        },
        {
          title: "No Hot Reload",
          desc: "Changed one line of CSS? Hit Ctrl+R and wait for the entire page to reload. Every. Single. Time.",
          icon: "🔄",
        },
        {
          title: "Global Scope Pollution",
          desc: 'Every variable was window.something. Two files both define "init()"? Last one wins. Good luck debugging that.',
          icon: "💥",
        },
        {
          title: "No Optimization",
          desc: "The browser downloaded every single file separately — 15 script tags = 15 HTTP requests. On a slow connection, this was brutal.",
          icon: "🐌",
        },
        {
          title: "Copy-Paste Reuse",
          desc: 'Want the same header on 20 pages? Copy-paste the HTML into each file. Need to change it? Update all 20. Miss one? "Whoops."',
          icon: "📋",
        },
      ].map((pain) => (
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-amber-900/30 bg-amber-950/10 p-4">
          <div class="text-2xl mb-2">{pain.icon}</div>
          <h3 class="font-display font-bold text-amber-300 mb-1">
            {pain.title}
          </h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">{pain.desc}</p>
        </div>
      ))
    }
  </div>

  <Callout color="#fbbf24" icon="📄">
    <strong class="text-amber-300">File extensions you'll see:</strong> In the old
    days, it was simple — <code
      class="font-mono text-xs bg-zinc-800 px-1 rounded text-amber-200"
      >.html</code
    > for markup, <code
      class="font-mono text-xs bg-zinc-800 px-1 rounded text-amber-200"
      >.css</code
    > for styles, and <code
      class="font-mono text-xs bg-zinc-800 px-1 rounded text-amber-200"
      >.js</code
    > for JavaScript. The <code
      class="font-mono text-xs bg-zinc-800 px-1 rounded text-amber-200"
      >.js</code
    > extension means "plain JavaScript" and it's still the most common one you'll
    see. As we go through this guide, you'll learn about new extensions that build
    on top of it.
  </Callout>

  <Callout color="#fbbf24" icon="🧠">
    <strong class="text-amber-300">The takeaway:</strong> Raw HTML/CSS/JS works, and
    it's how the web started. But as apps grew bigger, developers needed better tools
    to manage complexity. That's what the rest of this guide is about — the tools
    that make modern web development actually bearable.
  </Callout>
</div>
